Comment: I had white pieces and started with e4.
stegal played e5, very standard move
Nf3 was played, attacking e5 pawn.
black played d6, indicates that he is going for Philidor's defense.
I played d4, challenging the e5 pawn immediately, also making way for the lsb.
exd4 was played, this is known as the exchange variation of Philidor's defense.
Nxd4, stand move.
This move actually surprise me, black didn't play a normal looking move such as Nf6 or g6, but c5 was played, attacking the knight.
Nf3 was played, this wasn't an accurate move, may be Bb5+ is stronger, because Nf3 allows black to play Bg4.
Bg4, pins the knight :(
Be2 unpin, but I really don't like the position of my lsb :(

To my surprise again, Bxf3 was played! black gives up his lsb. If I were black I would keep the lsb, instead of playing bxf3 I would play g6 and prepare for Bg7, because pawns on c5 and d6 is blocking the dsb. Bg7 allows the dsb to work on a better diagonal.
never mind, Bxf3
Nc6 develops the knight.
develop my knight
more developing move from black
Bg5, develop my dsb and pin the knight.
be7 unpins, also black is now ready to castle king side.
Qd2, preparing queen side castle, safety first, so i can then launch the attack on black king.
O-O!
